TextBody:
Team,

Thank you for reaching out to support. 

To update/confirm our Technical Support Notes & start the investigation, could we get the text output (copy&past) from the following ADMIN PowerShell ISE script block on the systems that are running Netwrix/Stealth Server applications?

Clear-Host  # Clears the console window for better readability. 
#Netwrix/Stealth, PostgreSQL, Python application versions:
Get-CimInstance -Class Win32_Product |
Where-Object {($_.Name -Like "Stealth*" -or $_.Name -like "Netwrix*" -or $_.Name -like "*Postg*" -or ` $_.Name -like "Python*")} -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
Sort-Object | Format-Table Name,Version,InstallDate -AutoSize 

#Netwrix Enterprise Auditor (NEA) formally StealthAUDIT (SA) install path
$env:SAINSTALLDIR 

#Netwrix Access Information Center (AIC) formally StealthAUDIT Access Information Center (AIC) install path
(Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:SYSTEMCurrentControlSetServicesAccessInformationCenter"-ErrorAction SilentlyContinue).ImagePath.Replace("`"", "").Replace("BinAccessInformationCenter.Service.exe", "")

I will check with Dev for the best answer to the posted Question.

Thank You for your time.

Dusty Grayson
Sr. Support Engineer

TextBody:
Alison,

I asked for consensus on the following from Dev and will get what they say as soon as possible.

Based on the document âAzure Permissions for Modern Authentication - SPAAâ

Delegated vs. Application Permissions:

Delegated permissions are used when an app acts on behalf of a signed-in user, while application permissions are used when the app acts on its own identity, without a signed-in user. For instance, if a scan needs to access data that canât be scoped to a single user or when user interaction is not feasible, application permissions are used.

Requirement of Delegated Permissions: 

Delegated permissions are required when the scan needs to act on behalf of a user, with the userâs consent, and access resources based on the userâs privileges within the organization1. This is necessary for scenarios where the application needs to perform actions that are specific to a userâs role or access rights, such as accessing user-specific data or performing tasks that require user authorization.

External references

Authentication and authorization basics - Microsoft Graph | Microsoft Learn

Overview of permissions and consent in the Microsoft identity platform - Microsoft identity platform | Microsoft Learn

 


	
		
			
			Permission types
			
			
			Delegated permissions
			
			
			Application permissions
			
		
		
			
			Types of apps
			
			
			Web / Mobile / single-page app (SPA)
			
			
			Web / Daemon
			
		
		
			
			Access context
			
			
			Get access on behalf of a user
			
			
			Get access without a user
			
		
		
			
			Who can consent
			
			
			- Users can consent for their data
			
			
			Only admin can consent
			
		
		
			
			 
			
			
			- Admins can consent for all users
			
			
			 
			
		
		
			
			Consent methods
			
			
			- Static: configured list on app registration
			
			
			- Static ONLY: configured list on app registration
			
		
		
			
			 
			
			
			- Dynamic: request individual permissions at login
			
			
			 
			
		
		
			
			Other names
			
			
			- Scopes
			
			
			- App roles
			
		
		
			
			 
			
			
			- OAuth2 permission scopes
			
			
			- App-only permissions
			
		
		
			
			Result of consent (specific to Microsoft Graph)
			
			
			OAuth2PermissionGrant
			
			
			appRoleAssignment

TextBody:
ref:_00D7091pB._500Q000BUCdL:ref

Hi Dusty,
Currently in v11.5, we have StealthAudit registered with a client ID and secret to scan Sharepoint online.

Before closing this ticket, would you please advise:
In v11.6, to scan SharePoint Online, does StealthAudit need to be registered in Azure? If so, does it require access to the Azure AD Inventory Data Collector i.e register StealthAudit as a web application with Microsoft Entra ID client ID and secret as well as being registered with a SharePoint Client ID and secret?

Would you also please advise:

  *   why do we need the same SharePoint permissions (Sites.Read.All, User.Read)
  *   do we require Delegated or Application permissions?
  *   Sites.Read.All Why do we need same - REQUEST in Graph API
  *   User.Read.All Why do we need same - REQUEST in Graph API


We are being asked why we need duplicate permissions:


  *   Microsoft Graph permissions:
     *   Application.Read.All - Allows the app to read all applications and service principals without a signed-in user.
     *   AuditLog.Read.All - Allows the app to read and query your audit log activities, without a signed-in user.
     *   Directory.Read.All - Allows the app to read data in your organization's directory, such as users, groups and apps, without a signed-in user.
     *   Domain.Read.All - Allows the app to read all domain properties without a signed-in user.
     *   Files.Read.All - Allows the app to read all files in all site collections without a signed in user.
     *   Group.Read.All - Allows the app to read group properties and memberships, and read conversations for all groups, without a signed-in user.

Additional links you provided list Group.Read.All  needing Delegate  access (SharePoint Online Permissions (netwrix.com)<https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/EnterpriseAuditor_11.6/page/Content/EnterpriseAuditor/Requirements/Solutions/SharePoint/OnlinePermissions.htm>, AzureADInventory Data Collector (netwrix.com)<https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/EnterpriseAuditor_11.6/page/Content/EnterpriseAuditor/Admin/DataCollector/AzureADInventory/Overview.htm>)



     *   GroupMember.Read.All - Allows the app to read memberships and basic group properties for all groups without a signed-in user.
     *   InformationProtectionPolicy.Read.All - Allows an app to read published sensitivity labels and label policy settings for the entire organization or a specific user, without a signed in user.
     *   Member.Read.Hidden - Allows the app to read the memberships of hidden groups and administrative units without a signed-in user.
     *   Organization.Read.All - Allows the app to read the organization and related resources, without a signed-in user. Related resources include things like subscribed skus and tenant branding information.
     *   OrgContact.Read.All - Allows the app to read all organizational contacts without a signed-in user. These contacts are managed by the organization and are different from a user's personal contacts.
     *   Policy.Read.All - Allows the app to read all your organization's policies without a signed in user.
     *   Policy.Read.ConditionalAccess - Allows the app to read your organization's conditional access policies, without a signed-in user.
     *   Policy.Read.PermissionGrant - Allows the app to read policies related to consent and permission grants for applications, without a signed-in user.
     *   ServiceHealth.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service health information, without a signed-in user. Health information may include service issues or service health overviews.
     *   ServiceMessage.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service announcement messages, without a signed-in user. Messages may include information about new or changed features.
     *   Sites.Read.All - Allows the app to read documents and list items in all site collections without a signed in user.

Why do you need same SharePoint permissions below (Sites.Read.All, User.Read)

     *   Team.ReadBasic.All - Get a list of all teams, without a signed-in user.
     *   TeamMember.Read.All - Read the members of all teams, without a signed-in user.



     *   User.Read - Allows you to sign in to the app with your organizational account and let the app read your profile. It also allows the app to read basic company information. * This is a user level permission, rather than an application level permission, and is used to allow the application to log in as it's security principal.

This   User.Read   Delegate   permission is not listed as being required  in any of the 2  links you have provided.

It was not listed as requirement in your original RTIM  request.  It only lists User.Read.All



     *   User.Read.All - Allows the app to read user profiles without a signed in user. * These are Azure ADI users.

Also both links  you provide  (I have added below)  list needing Delegated  permissions  but  you have  them  down for  Application permission here .

Your  original  RTIM lists  it need  Delegate permissions  ,  but  it is Deployed   Application permission in  TST today. Do you require Delegated or Application permissions?

Hi Dusty,

Currently in v11.5, we have StealthAudit registered with a client ID and secret to scan Sharepoint online.

 

Before closing this ticket, would you please advise:

In v11.6, to scan SharePoint Online, does StealthAudit need to be registered in Azure? If so, does it require access to the Azure AD Inventory Data Collector i.e register StealthAudit as a web application with Microsoft Entra ID client ID and secret as well as being registered with a SharePoint Client ID and secret?

 

Would you also please advise: 


	why do we need the same SharePoint permissions (Sites.Read.All, User.Read) 
	do we require Delegated or Application permissions?
	Sites.Read.All Why do we need same - REQUEST in Graph API
	User.Read.All Why do we need same - REQUEST in Graph API


 

 

We are being asked why we need duplicate permissions:

 


	Microsoft Graph permissions:
	
		Application.Read.All - Allows the app to read all applications and service principals without a signed-in user.
		AuditLog.Read.All - Allows the app to read and query your audit log activities, without a signed-in user.
		Directory.Read.All - Allows the app to read data in your organization's directory, such as users, groups and apps, without a signed-in user.
		Domain.Read.All - Allows the app to read all domain properties without a signed-in user.
		Files.Read.All - Allows the app to read all files in all site collections without a signed in user.
		Group.Read.All - Allows the app to read group properties and memberships, and read conversations for all groups, without a signed-in user.
	
	


Additional links you provided list Group.Read.All  needing Delegate  access (SharePoint Online Permissions (netwrix.com),  AzureADInventory Data Collector (netwrix.com))

 


	
	
		GroupMember.Read.All - Allows the app to read memberships and basic group properties for all groups without a signed-in user.
		InformationProtectionPolicy.Read.All - Allows an app to read published sensitivity labels and label policy settings for the entire organization or a specific user, without a signed in user.
		Member.Read.Hidden - Allows the app to read the memberships of hidden groups and administrative units without a signed-in user.
		Organization.Read.All - Allows the app to read the organization and related resources, without a signed-in user. Related resources include things like subscribed skus and tenant branding information.
		OrgContact.Read.All - Allows the app to read all organizational contacts without a signed-in user. These contacts are managed by the organization and are different from a user's personal contacts.
		Policy.Read.All - Allows the app to read all your organization's policies without a signed in user.
		Policy.Read.ConditionalAccess - Allows the app to read your organization's conditional access policies, without a signed-in user.
		Policy.Read.PermissionGrant - Allows the app to read policies related to consent and permission grants for applications, without a signed-in user.
		ServiceHealth.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service health information, without a signed-in user. Health information may include service issues or service health overviews.
		ServiceMessage.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service announcement messages, without a signed-in user. Messages may include information about new or changed features.
		Sites.Read.All - Allows the app to read documents and list items in all site collections without a signed in user.
	
	


Why do you need same SharePoint permissions below (Sites.Read.All, User.Read)


	
	
		Team.ReadBasic.All - Get a list of all teams, without a signed-in user.
		TeamMember.Read.All - Read the members of all teams, without a signed-in user.
	
	


 


	
	
		User.Read - Allows you to sign in to the app with your organizational account and let the app read your profile. It also allows the app to read basic company information. * This is a user level permission, rather than an application level permission, and is used to allow the application to log in as it's security principal.
	
	


This   User.Read   Delegate   permission is not listed as being required  in any of the 2  links you have provided. 

It was not listed as requirement in your original RTIM  request.  It only lists User.Read.All

 


	
	
		User.Read.All - Allows the app to read user profiles without a signed in user. * These are Azure ADI users.
	
	


Also both links  you provide  (I have added below)  list needing Delegated  permissions  but  you have  them  down for  Application permission here .

Your  original  RTIM lists  it need  Delegate permissions  ,  but  it is Deployed   Application permission in  TST today. Do you require Delegated or Application permissions?

 

Office 365 Management API permissions:


	
	
		ActivityFeed,Read - Allows the application to read activity data for your organization.
		ActivityFeed.Read.Dlp - Allows the application to read DLP policy events, including detected sensitive data, for your organization.
		ServiceHealth.Read - Allows the application to read service health information for your organization.
	
	


 


	SharePoint permissions:

	
		Sites.FullControll.All - Allows the app to have full control of all site collections without a signed in user. * This permission is used to query for the list of all site collections. Without this permission SPAA can not find all site collections.
		Sites.Read.All - Allows the app to read documents and list items in all site collections without a signed in user. * This permission is used to read the hierarchy data within individual site collections.
	
	


Why do you need same - REQUEST in Graph API


	
	
		TermStore.Read.All - Allows the app to read enterprise managed metadata and to read basic site info without a signed in user.
		User.Read.All - Allows the app to read user profiles without a signed in user. * These are SharePoint users.
		Why do you need same - REQUEST in Graph API
	
	


 

Thank you,

Alison.

We are being asked why we need duplicate permissions:

 


	Microsoft Graph permissions:



	
	
		Application.Read.All - Allows the app to read all applications and service principals without a signed-in user.
		AuditLog.Read.All - Allows the app to read and query your audit log activities, without a signed-in user.
		Directory.Read.All - Allows the app to read data in your organization's directory, such as users, groups and apps, without a signed-in user.
		Domain.Read.All - Allows the app to read all domain properties without a signed-in user.
		Files.Read.All - Allows the app to read all files in all site collections without a signed in user.
		Group.Read.All - Allows the app to read group properties and memberships, and read conversations for all groups, without a signed-in user.
	
	


Additional links you provided list Group.Read.All  needing Delegate  access (SharePoint Online Permissions (netwrix.com),  AzureADInventory Data Collector (netwrix.com))

		GroupMember.Read.All - Allows the app to read memberships and basic group properties for all groups without a signed-in user.
		InformationProtectionPolicy.Read.All - Allows an app to read published sensitivity labels and label policy settings for the entire organization or a specific user, without a signed in user.
		Member.Read.Hidden - Allows the app to read the memberships of hidden groups and administrative units without a signed-in user.
		Organization.Read.All - Allows the app to read the organization and related resources, without a signed-in user. Related resources include things like subscribed skus and tenant branding information.
		OrgContact.Read.All - Allows the app to read all organizational contacts without a signed-in user. These contacts are managed by the organization and are different from a user's personal contacts.
		Policy.Read.All - Allows the app to read all your organization's policies without a signed in user.
		Policy.Read.ConditionalAccess - Allows the app to read your organization's conditional access policies, without a signed-in user.
		Policy.Read.PermissionGrant - Allows the app to read policies related to consent and permission grants for applications, without a signed-in user.
		ServiceHealth.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service health information, without a signed-in user. Health information may include service issues or service health overviews.
		ServiceMessage.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service announcement messages, without a signed-in user. Messages may include information about new or changed features.
		Sites.Read.All - Allows the app to read documents and list items in all site collections without a signed in user.
	
	


Why do you need same SharePoint permissions below (Sites.Read.All, User.Read)

Â·         


	
	
		Team.ReadBasic.All - Get a list of all teams, without a signed-in user.
		TeamMember.Read.All - Read the members of all teams, without a signed-in user.
	
	


 

Â·         


	
	
		User.Read - Allows you to sign in to the app with your organizational account and let the app read your profile. It also allows the app to read basic company information. * This is a user level permission, rather than an application level permission, and is used to allow the application to log in as it's security principal.
	
	


This   User.Read   Delegate   permission is not listed as being required  in any of the 2  links you have provided. 

It was not listed as requirement in your original RTIM  request.  It only lists User.Read.All

 

Â·         


	
	
		User.Read.All - Allows the app to read user profiles without a signed in user. * These are Azure ADI users.
	
	


Also both links  you provide  (I have added below)  list needing Delegated  permissions  but  you have  them  down for  Application permission here .

Your  original  RTIM lists  it need  Delegate permissions  ,  but  it is Deployed   Application permission in  TST today. Do you require Delegated or Application permissions?

 

Office 365 Management API permissions:

Â·         


	
	
		ActivityFeed,Read - Allows the application to read activity data for your organization.
		ActivityFeed.Read.Dlp - Allows the application to read DLP policy events, including detected sensitive data, for your organization.
		ServiceHealth.Read - Allows the application to read service health information for your organization.
	
	


 


	SharePoint permissions:



	
	
		Sites.FullControll.All - Allows the app to have full control of all site collections without a signed in user. * This permission is used to query for the list of all site collections. Without this permission SPAA can not find all site collections.
		Sites.Read.All - Allows the app to read documents and list items in all site collections without a signed in user. * This permission is used to read the hierarchy data within individual site collections.
	
	


Why do you need same - REQUEST in Graph API

Â·         


	
	
		TermStore.Read.All - Allows the app to read enterprise managed metadata and to read basic site info without a signed in user.
		User.Read.All - Allows the app to read user profiles without a signed in user. * These are SharePoint users.
		Why do you need same - REQUEST in Graph API

Hi Dusty,

Currently in v11.5, we have StealthAudit registered with a client ID and secret to scan Sharepoint online.

 

Before closing this ticket, would you please advise:

In v11.6, to scan SharePoint Online, does StealthAudit need to be registered in Azure? If so, does it require access to the Azure AD Inventory Data Collector i.e register StealthAudit as a web application with Microsoft Entra ID client ID and secret as well as being registered with a SharePoint Client ID and secret?

 

Would you also please advise: 


	why do we need the same SharePoint permissions (Sites.Read.All, User.Read)
	do we require Delegated or Application permissions?
	Sites.Read.All Why do we need same - REQUEST in Graph API
	User.Read.All Why do we need same - REQUEST in Graph API


 

 

We are being asked why we need duplicate permissions:

 


	Microsoft Graph permissions:



	
	
		Application.Read.All - Allows the app to read all applications and service principals without a signed-in user.
		AuditLog.Read.All - Allows the app to read and query your audit log activities, without a signed-in user.
		Directory.Read.All - Allows the app to read data in your organization's directory, such as users, groups and apps, without a signed-in user.
		Domain.Read.All - Allows the app to read all domain properties without a signed-in user.
		Files.Read.All - Allows the app to read all files in all site collections without a signed in user.
		Group.Read.All - Allows the app to read group properties and memberships, and read conversations for all groups, without a signed-in user.
	
	


Additional links you provided list Group.Read.All  needing Delegate  access (SharePoint Online Permissions (netwrix.com),  AzureADInventory Data Collector (netwrix.com))

 

Â·         


	
	
		GroupMember.Read.All - Allows the app to read memberships and basic group properties for all groups without a signed-in user.
		InformationProtectionPolicy.Read.All - Allows an app to read published sensitivity labels and label policy settings for the entire organization or a specific user, without a signed in user.
		Member.Read.Hidden - Allows the app to read the memberships of hidden groups and administrative units without a signed-in user.
		Organization.Read.All - Allows the app to read the organization and related resources, without a signed-in user. Related resources include things like subscribed skus and tenant branding information.
		OrgContact.Read.All - Allows the app to read all organizational contacts without a signed-in user. These contacts are managed by the organization and are different from a user's personal contacts.
		Policy.Read.All - Allows the app to read all your organization's policies without a signed in user.
		Policy.Read.ConditionalAccess - Allows the app to read your organization's conditional access policies, without a signed-in user.
		Policy.Read.PermissionGrant - Allows the app to read policies related to consent and permission grants for applications, without a signed-in user.
		ServiceHealth.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service health information, without a signed-in user. Health information may include service issues or service health overviews.
		ServiceMessage.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service announcement messages, without a signed-in user. Messages may include information about new or changed features.
		Sites.Read.All - Allows the app to read documents and list items in all site collections without a signed in user.
	
	


Why do you need same SharePoint permissions below (Sites.Read.All, User.Read)

Â·         


	
	
		Team.ReadBasic.All - Get a list of all teams, without a signed-in user.
		TeamMember.Read.All - Read the members of all teams, without a signed-in user.
	
	


 

Â·         


	
	
		User.Read - Allows you to sign in to the app with your organizational account and let the app read your profile. It also allows the app to read basic company information. * This is a user level permission, rather than an application level permission, and is used to allow the application to log in as it's security principal.
	
	


This   User.Read   Delegate   permission is not listed as being required  in any of the 2  links you have provided. 

It was not listed as requirement in your original RTIM  request.  It only lists User.Read.All

 

Â·         


	
	
		User.Read.All - Allows the app to read user profiles without a signed in user. * These are Azure ADI users.
	
	


Also both links  you provide  (I have added below)  list needing Delegated  permissions  but  you have  them  down for  Application permission here .

Your  original  RTIM lists  it need  Delegate permissions  ,  but  it is Deployed   Application permission in  TST today. Do you require Delegated or Application permissions?

 

Office 365 Management API permissions:

Â·         


	
	
		ActivityFeed,Read - Allows the application to read activity data for your organization.
		ActivityFeed.Read.Dlp - Allows the application to read DLP policy events, including detected sensitive data, for your organization.
		ServiceHealth.Read - Allows the application to read service health information for your organization.
	
	


 


	SharePoint permissions:



	
	
		Sites.FullControll.All - Allows the app to have full control of all site collections without a signed in user. * This permission is used to query for the list of all site collections. Without this permission SPAA can not find all site collections.
		Sites.Read.All - Allows the app to read documents and list items in all site collections without a signed in user. * This permission is used to read the hierarchy data within individual site collections.
	
	


Why do you need same - REQUEST in Graph API

Â·         


	
	
		TermStore.Read.All - Allows the app to read enterprise managed metadata and to read basic site info without a signed in user.
		User.Read.All - Allows the app to read user profiles without a signed in user. * These are SharePoint users.
		Why do you need same - REQUEST in Graph API
	
	


 

Thank you,

Alison.

Hi Allison,

See the additional explanation below:

We leverage two sets of permissions due to the fact that Microsoft Graph API provides us with some information, while we leverage other APIs to get additional information. This is why we see two sets of permission requirements for Sites.Read.All and Groups.Read.All. 

Sites.FullControll.All - This permission is used to query for the list of all site collections. We have tested with lower privileges and raised queries with Microsoft to confirm that this permission is required in order to enumerate site collections and child objects. 

Let me know if you have any additional questions. 

Thanks,
Farrah Gamboa

In v11.6, to scan SharePoint Online, does StealthAudit need to be registered in Azure? 	why do we need the same SharePoint permissions (Sites.Read.All, User.Read)
	do we require Delegated or Application permissions?
	Sites.Read.All Why do we need same - REQUEST in Graph API
	User.Read.All Why do we need same - REQUEST in Graph API


 

 

We are being asked why we need duplicate permissions:

 


	Microsoft Graph permissions:



	 



	
	
		Application.Read.All - Allows the app to read all applications and service principals without a signed-in user.
		AuditLog.Read.All - Allows the app to read and query your audit log activities, without a signed-in user.
		Directory.Read.All - Allows the app to read data in your organization's directory, such as users, groups and apps, without a signed-in user.
		Domain.Read.All - Allows the app to read all domain properties without a signed-in user.
		Files.Read.All - Allows the app to read all files in all site collections without a signed in user.
		Group.Read.All - Allows the app to read group properties and memberships, and read conversations for all groups, without a signed-in user.
	
	


Additional links you provided list Group.Read.All  needing Delegate  access (SharePoint Online Permissions (netwrix.com), AzureADInventory Data Collector (netwrix.com))

 

1.       


	 



	
	
		GroupMember.Read.All - Allows the app to read memberships and basic group properties for all groups without a signed-in user.
		InformationProtectionPolicy.Read.All - Allows an app to read published sensitivity labels and label policy settings for the entire organization or a specific user, without a signed in user.
		Member.Read.Hidden - Allows the app to read the memberships of hidden groups and administrative units without a signed-in user.
		Organization.Read.All - Allows the app to read the organization and related resources, without a signed-in user. Related resources include things like subscribed skus and tenant branding information.
		OrgContact.Read.All - Allows the app to read all organizational contacts without a signed-in user. These contacts are managed by the organization and are different from a user's personal contacts.
		Policy.Read.All - Allows the app to read all your organization's policies without a signed in user.
		Policy.Read.ConditionalAccess - Allows the app to read your organization's conditional access policies, without a signed-in user.
		Policy.Read.PermissionGrant - Allows the app to read policies related to consent and permission grants for applications, without a signed-in user.
		ServiceHealth.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service health information, without a signed-in user. Health information may include service issues or service health overviews.
		ServiceMessage.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service announcement messages, without a signed-in user. Messages may include information about new or changed features.
		Sites.Read.All - Allows the app to read documents and list items in all site collections without a signed in user.
	
	


Why do you need same SharePoint permissions below (Sites.Read.All, User.Read)

1.       


	 



	
	
		Team.ReadBasic.All - Get a list of all teams, without a signed-in user.
		TeamMember.Read.All - Read the members of all teams, without a signed-in user.

Hi Allison,

See the additional explanation below:

We leverage two sets of permissions due to the fact that Microsoft Graph API provides us with some information, while we leverage other APIs to get additional information. This is why we see two sets of permission requirements for Sites.Read.All and Groups.Read.All. 

Sites.FullControll.All - This permission is used to query for the list of all site collections. We have tested with lower privileges and raised queries with Microsoft to confirm that this permission is required in order to enumerate site collections and child objects. 

Let me know if you have any additional questions. 

Thanks,

	Microsoft Graph permissions:



	 



	
	
		Application.Read.All - Allows the app to read all applications and service principals without a signed-in user.
		AuditLog.Read.All - Allows the app to read and query your audit log activities, without a signed-in user.
		Directory.Read.All - Allows the app to read data in your organization's directory, such as users, groups and apps, without a signed-in user.
		Domain.Read.All - Allows the app to read all domain properties without a signed-in user.
		Files.Read.All - Allows the app to read all files in all site collections without a signed in user.
		Group.Read.All - Allows the app to read group properties and memberships, and read conversations for all groups, without a signed-in user.
	
	


Additional links you provided list Group.Read.All  needing Delegate  access (SharePoint Online Permissions (netwrix.com), AzureADInventory Data Collector (netwrix.com))

 

1.       


	 



	
	
		GroupMember.Read.All - Allows the app to read memberships and basic group properties for all groups without a signed-in user.
		InformationProtectionPolicy.Read.All - Allows an app to read published sensitivity labels and label policy settings for the entire organization or a specific user, without a signed in user.
		Member.Read.Hidden - Allows the app to read the memberships of hidden groups and administrative units without a signed-in user.
		Organization.Read.All - Allows the app to read the organization and related resources, without a signed-in user. Related resources include things like subscribed skus and tenant branding information.
		OrgContact.Read.All - Allows the app to read all organizational contacts without a signed-in user. These contacts are managed by the organization and are different from a user's personal contacts.
		Policy.Read.All - Allows the app to read all your organization's policies without a signed in user.
		Policy.Read.ConditionalAccess - Allows the app to read your organization's conditional access policies, without a signed-in user.
		Policy.Read.PermissionGrant - Allows the app to read policies related to consent and permission grants for applications, without a signed-in user.
		ServiceHealth.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service health information, without a signed-in user. Health information may include service issues or service health overviews.
		ServiceMessage.Read.All - Allows the app to read your tenant's service announcement messages, without a signed-in user. Messages may include information about new or changed features.
		Sites.Read.All - Allows the app to read documents and list items in all site collections without a signed in user.
